ecessionists at Bay, 1776\u20131854'' (1991), emphasis on slavery\n* Gienapp, William E. ''The Origins of the Republican Party, 1852\u20131856'' (1987)\n* Manning, Chandra. ''What This Cruel War Was Over: Soldiers, Slavery, and the Civil War.'' New York: Vintage Books (2007)\n* {{cite newspaper\n|first=Byron\n|last=McCauley\n|title=The Confederacy was about preserving slavery. The proof? It's on the money\n|date=April 5, 2018\n|url=https://www.cincinnati.com/story/news/2018/04/05/confederacy-preserving-slavery-proof-its-money/489694002/\n|newspaper=[[The Cincinnati Enquirer]]\n|access-date=April 15, 2018}}\n* McPherson, James M. ''Battle Cry of Freedom: The Civil War Era'' (1988), major overview, neo-abolitionist emphasis on slavery\n* Morrison, Michael. ''Slavery and the American West: The Eclipse of Manifest Destiny and the Coming of the Civil War'' (1997)\n* Morrow, Ralph E.  \"The Proslavery Argument Revisited\", ''The Mississippi Valley Historical Review'', Vol. 48, No. 1. (June 1961), pp.&nbsp;79\u201394. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/1902405 in JSTOR] (Maintains that antebellum pro-slavery writing was not intended to, or not solely intended to, convince Northerners, but was written and published to reduce the guilt felt by many in slave states.)\n* Oakes, James. ''The Scorpion's Sting: Antislavery and the Coming of the Civil War'' (New York: Norton, 2014) 207 pp.\n* Rhodes, James Ford. ''History of the United States from the Compromise of 1850 to the McKinley-Bryan Campaign of 1896'' Volume: 1 (1920), highly detailed narrative 1850\u201356. Vol 2 1856\u201360; emphasis on slavery\n* [[Arthur Schlesinger Jr.|Schlesinger, Arthur Jr.]] \"The Causes of the Civil War\" (1949), reprinted in his ''The Politics of Hope'' (1963); reintroduced new emphasis on slavery\n* Stampp, Kenneth M. ''America in 1857: A Nation on the Brink'' (1990)\n* Stampp, Kenneth M. ''And the War Came: The North and the Secession Crisis, 1860\u20131861'' (1950)\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote|American Civil War}}\n* [http://tigger.uic.edu/~rjensen/civwar.htm Civil War and Reconstruction: Jensen's Guide to WWW Resources]\n* [http://www.brown.edu/Research/Slavery_Justice/documents/SlaveryAndJustice.pdf Report of the Brown University Steering Committee on Slavery and Justice]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120825102042/http://www.mit.edu/~mi22295/elections.html State by state popular vote for president in 1860 election]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120825102042/http://www.mit.edu/~mi22295/elections.html Tulane course \u2013 article on 1860 election]\n* [http://www.tulane.edu/~sumter/ Tulane course \u2013 article on Fort Sumter]\n* [http://www.albany.edu/talkinghistory/index.html Onuf, Peter. \"Making Two Nations: The Origins of the Civil War\". 2003 speech]\n* [http://www.gilderlehrman.org/ The Gilder Lehrman Institute of American History]\n* [http://www.civilwar.com/ CivilWar.com], many source materials, including states' secession declarations\n* [http://civilwarcauses.org/ Causes of the Civil War], collection of primary documents\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150213033216/http://civilwarcauses.org/reasons.htm Declarations of Causes of Seceding States]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051201024514/http://civilwartalk.com/cwt_alt/resources/documents/cornerstone_addy.htm Alexander H. Stephens' Cornerstone Address]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051103073639/http://www.adena.com/adena/usa/cw/cw223.htm An entry from Alexander Stephens' diary, dated 1866, reflecting on the origins of the Civil War]\n* [http://muse.jhu.edu/demo/civil_war_history/v046/46.4huston.html The Arguments of the Constitutional Unionists in 1850\u201351]\n* [http://www.shmoop.com/causes-of-civil-war/ Shmoop US History: Causes of the Civil War], study guide, dates, trivia, multimedia, teachers' guide\n* [https://www.c-span.org/video/?80568-1/approaching-fury ''Booknotes'' interview with Stephen B. Oates on ''The Approaching Fury: Voices of the Storm, 1820\u20131861'', 